()evaluate ya evaluation ka matlab in sailpoint ?
--kisi rule, policy, ya condition ko check karna ki wo satisfy ho rahi hai ya nahi.

🔹 1. Simple Example (Real Life):-
Maan lo:-
👉 Rule: “User ka role Admin nahi hona chahiye”
Evaluation kya karega?
User ka data lega
Check karega: kya role = Admin hai?
Result dega: ✅ Pass / ❌ Fail

🔹 2. SailPoint me Evaluation kaha use hota hai?
1️⃣ Policy Evaluation:-
👉 Jab policies run hoti hain
Example:-
SoD Policy (Segregation of Duties)
Password Policy
Access Policy
Process:-
Identity ka data uthata hai
Roles / Entitlements check karta hai
Violation hai ya nahi → evaluate karta hai.

2️⃣ Rule Evaluation:-
👉 SailPoint me bahut saare rules hote hain (Java based)
Example:-
if (identity.getDepartment().equals("IT")) {
    return true;
}
👉 Ye condition jab run hoti hai → isko evaluate bolte hain.

3️⃣ Provisioning me Evaluation:-
👉 Jab provisioning hoti hai (account create/update/delete)
Plan validate hota hai
Attributes check hote hain
Dependencies check hoti hain
👉 Ye sab internally evaluate hote hain.

4️⃣ Workflow Evaluation:-
👉 Workflow me conditions hoti hain:-
<Step condition="identity.manager != null">
👉 System evaluate karega:-
Manager hai ya nahi?
True → next step
False → skip

🔹 3. Technical Meaning (Important):-
👉 Evaluation ka matlab hota hai:-
✔ Expression execute karna
✔ Condition check karna
✔ Result return karna (true/false / value).

🔹 4. SailPoint me kaun evaluate karta hai?
Mostly ye components:-
PolicyEvaluator (policy check karta hai)
Rule Engine (rules run karta hai)
Workflow Engine (conditions check karta hai)
Provisioner (plan validate karta hai).
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
()PolicyEvaluator kya hai?
👉 PolicyEvaluator ek engine hai jo policies ko evaluate karta hai.
👉 Matlab:-
Identity ka data uthata hai
Policies apply karta hai
Check karta hai violation hai ya nahi.

🔹 Ye karta kya hai? (Step-by-step flow)
🧠 Internal Working:-
1️⃣ Identity uthata hai:-
Identity identity = context.getObjectByName(Identity.class, "rahul");

2️⃣ Policies load karta hai:-
SoD Policies
Activity Policies
Password Policies

3️⃣ Evaluate karta hai:-
👉 Example:-
User ke paas:-
Role A
Role B

👉 Policy:-
“Role A + Role B ek saath allowed nahi hai”
👉 PolicyEvaluator kya karega?
Roles compare karega
Conflict check karega
Violation detect karega

4️⃣ Result banata hai
👉 Agar violation mila:-
PolicyViolation object create hota hai.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔹 DB me kya store hota hai? 💾
👉 Jab evaluation hoti hai, tab result DB me save hota hai (agar violation hai)

📌 1️⃣ PolicyViolation Table:-
👉 Ye sabse important hai,
Store hota hai:-
Identity ID
Policy Name
Violation Type
Status (Open / Closed)
Date
👉 Example:-
Identity	Policy	       Status
Rahul	    SoD Conflict	Open

📌 2️⃣ spt_policy Table:-
👉 Policies khud yahan store hoti hain,
Store hota hai:-
Policy name
Type (SoD / Activity)
Rule reference
Description

📌 3️⃣ spt_identity Table:-
👉 User ka data.

📌 4️⃣ spt_policy_violation (Main table):-
👉 Actual violations yahan save hote hain.

🔹 DB me kya store nahi hota?
❌ Evaluation ka process (runtime logic).
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1️⃣ evaluate():-
List<PolicyViolation> evaluate(Identity identity)
👉 Kya karta hai?
Ek identity ke against saari policies run karta hai
Violations return karta hai
👉 Example:-
PolicyEvaluator evaluator = new PolicyEvaluator(context);
List<PolicyViolation> violations = evaluator.evaluate(identity);

for (PolicyViolation v : violations) {
    System.out.println(v.getPolicyName());
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2️⃣ evaluate(identity, policies):-
List<PolicyViolation> evaluate(Identity identity, List<Policy> policies)
👉 Kya karta hai?
Sirf specific policies evaluate karta hai

3️⃣ evaluateAll():-
List<PolicyViolation> evaluateAll():-
👉 Kya karta hai?
System ke sab identities ko evaluate karta hai
👉 Heavy operation (batch jobs me use hota hai).
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4️⃣ evaluatePolicy():-
List<PolicyViolation> evaluatePolicy(Identity identity, Policy policy)
👉 Kya karta hai?
Ek identity + ek policy check karta hai.

🔹 evaluateWithOptions() kya hai?
👉 Ye method use hota hai jab tu custom control ke saath policy evaluation karna chahta hai,
List<PolicyViolation> evaluate(Identity identity, Map options)

👉 Yahan:-
identity → jis user ko evaluate karna hai
options → extra control/config.

🔹 Simple samajh:-
👉(1)Normal evaluate(identity):-
Default rules follow karta hai.

👉(2)evaluate(identity, options):-
Tu bolta hai system ko:
“aise evaluate karo”
“ye ignore karo”
“ye include karo”

3️⃣ Ignore mitigations:-
options.put("ignoreMitigations", true);
👉 Agar violation already approved/mitigated hai
👉 To bhi dubara check karega

4️⃣ Role / Entitlement filtering:-
options.put("includeRoles", true);
options.put("includeEntitlements", true);
👉 Decide karta hai kya evaluate hoga.

5️⃣ Specific Policy type:-
options.put("policyType", "SoD");
👉 Sirf SoD policies evaluate karega.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔥 🔹 3. Helper / Internal Type Methods:-
👉 Ye methods directly tum use nahi karte but internally kaam karte hain:-

6️⃣ checkPolicyRules():-
Policy ke andar jo rule hai usko run karta hai

7️⃣ detectViolations():-
Conflict find karta hai

8️⃣ buildViolation():-
PolicyViolation object create karta hai.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
import sailpoint.api.SailPointContext;
import sailpoint.api.SailPointContextFactory;
import sailpoint.api.PolicyEvaluator;
import sailpoint.object.Identity;
import sailpoint.object.Policy;
import sailpoint.object.PolicyViolation;

import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;

public class PolicyEvaluatorDemo {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        SailPointContextFactory factory = new SailPointContextFactory();
        SailPointContext context = factory.getContext();

        Identity identity = context.getObjectByName(Identity.class, "rahul");

        PolicyEvaluator evaluator = new PolicyEvaluator(context);
        List<Policy> policies = context.getObjects(Policy.class);

        List<PolicyViolation> violations = evaluator.evaluate(identity, policies);

        for (PolicyViolation v : violations) {
            System.out.println("Policy: " + v.getPolicyName());
            System.out.println("Status: " + v.getStatus());
        }
		context.close();
    }
}
🔹 Output:-
Policy: Finance-Audit Conflict
Status: Open
Policy: Password Policy
Status: Open
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
import sailpoint.api.SailPointContext;
import sailpoint.api.SailPointContextFactory;
import sailpoint.api.PolicyEvaluator;
import sailpoint.object.Identity;
import sailpoint.object.Policy;
import sailpoint.object.PolicyViolation;

import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;

public class PolicyEvaluatorDemo {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        SailPointContextFactory factory = new SailPointContextFactory();
        SailPointContext context = factory.getContext();

        Identity identity = context.getObjectByName(Identity.class, "rahul");

        PolicyEvaluator evaluator = new PolicyEvaluator(context);
        List<PolicyViolation> allViolations = evaluator.evaluateAll();

        for (PolicyViolation v : allViolations) {
            System.out.println("Identity: " + v.getIdentity().getName());
            System.out.println("Policy: " + v.getPolicyName());
        }
		context.close();
    }
}
🔹 Output:-
Identity: rahul
Policy: SoD Conflict

Identity: amit
Policy: Password Policy
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
import sailpoint.api.SailPointContext;
import sailpoint.api.SailPointContextFactory;
import sailpoint.api.PolicyEvaluator;
import sailpoint.object.Identity;
import sailpoint.object.Policy;
import sailpoint.object.PolicyViolation;

import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;

public class PolicyEvaluatorDemo {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        SailPointContextFactory factory = new SailPointContextFactory();
        SailPointContext context = factory.getContext();

        Identity identity = context.getObjectByName(Identity.class, "rahul");

        PolicyEvaluator evaluator = new PolicyEvaluator(context);
        Policy policy = context.getObjectByName(Policy.class, "SoD Policy");

        List<PolicyViolation> result = evaluator.evaluate(identity, policy);

        for (PolicyViolation v : result) {
            System.out.println("Single Policy: " + v.getPolicyName());
            System.out.println("Status: " + v.getStatus());
        }
		context.close();
    }
}
🔹 Output:-
Single Policy: SoD Policy
Status: Open
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
import sailpoint.api.SailPointContext;
import sailpoint.api.SailPointContextFactory;
import sailpoint.api.PolicyEvaluator;
import sailpoint.object.Identity;
import sailpoint.object.Policy;
import sailpoint.object.PolicyViolation;

import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;

public class PolicyEvaluatorDemo {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        SailPointContextFactory factory = new SailPointContextFactory();
        SailPointContext context = factory.getContext();

        Identity identity = context.getObjectByName(Identity.class, "rahul");

        PolicyEvaluator evaluator = new PolicyEvaluator(context);
        Map<String, Object> options = new HashMap<String, Object>();

        options.put("ignoreMitigations", true);
        options.put("includeRoles", true);
        options.put("includeEntitlements", true);
        options.put("policyType", "SoD");

        List<PolicyViolation> resultWithOptions = evaluator.evaluate(identity, options);

        for (PolicyViolation v : resultWithOptions) {
            System.out.println("Policy (Options): " + v.getPolicyName());
            System.out.println("Status: " + v.getStatus());
        }
		context.close();
    }
}
🔹 Output:-
Policy (Options): Finance-Audit Conflict
Status: Open
Policy (Options): Admin Conflict
Status: Open

🔥 5️⃣ options.put():-
()options.put("ignoreMitigations", true);:-
👉 Already approved violations ko ignore nahi karega
👉 Dubara evaluate karega.

()options.put("includeRoles", true);:-
👉 Roles ko evaluation me include karega

()options.put("includeEntitlements", true);:-
👉 Entitlements (access rights) bhi check karega

()options.put("policyType", "SoD");:-
👉 Sirf SoD policies evaluate karega

🔚 Closing Code (End block)
        context.close();
    }
}
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
